  "prompt": "Is MSG as bad as usually claimed?",
  "response": "Monosodium glutamate (MSG) is a flavor enhancer commonly used in foods. It has been the subject of controversy and debate for many years, often being blamed for causing adverse reactions such as headaches, flushing, and sweating. This collection of symptoms is sometimes referred to as \"Chinese Restaurant Syndrome\" because MSG is frequently used in Asian cuisine.\n\nHowever, extensive scientific research has shown that MSG is generally safe for most people when consumed in normal dietary amounts. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has classified MSG as \"generally recognized as safe\" (GRAS), and many studies have not confirmed the widespread claims of adverse effects associated with it.\n\nSome individuals may have a sensitivity to MSG and experience mild symptoms following its consumption, but these occurrences are relatively rare. For most people, MSG does not present a significant health risk. It is always advisable to moderate your consumption of all additives and processed foods for overall health.\n\nIf someone has specific health concerns or symptoms they believe are related to MSG, they should consult with a healthcare professional for personalized advice.",
